# 1. Distributed Web Infrastructure

## Infrastructure

```text
User
  |
  | HTTP
  v
www.foobar.com
  |
  | DNS A Record
  v
8.8.8.8
  |
  v
+---------------------------+
|     Load Balancer         |
|        HAProxy            |
+------------+--------------+
             |
             | Round Robin
     +-------+-------+
     |               |
     v               v
+-----------+   +-----------+
| Server 1  |   | Server 2  |
|           |   |           |
| Nginx     |   | Nginx     |
| App Server|   | App Server|
| Code Base |   | Code Base |
| MySQL     |   | MySQL     |
| Primary   |   | Replica   |
+-----------+   +-----------+
```

## Explanation

A user wants to access the website `www.foobar.com`.

The browser asks DNS for the IP address of `www.foobar.com`.
The DNS record points `www.foobar.com` to the server IP address `8.8.8.8`.

The user request reaches the HAProxy load balancer.
The load balancer distributes the traffic between Server 1 and Server 2.

Each server contains:

* one web server: Nginx
* one application server
* one set of application files
* one MySQL database

## Why are we adding each element?

### Load balancer

We add a load balancer to distribute incoming traffic between multiple servers.

This improves availability and performance because one server does not have to handle all requests alone.

### Second server

We add a second server to reduce the load on the first server and to make the infrastructure more available.

If one application server becomes unavailable, the other one may still serve requests.

### Second web server

Each server has its own Nginx web server so it can receive and handle HTTP requests forwarded by the load balancer.

### Second application server

Each server has its own application server so both servers can execute the application logic.

### Second code base

Each server has a copy of the application files so both servers can run the same website.

### Second database

The second database is used as a replica of the primary database.

This helps distribute database reads and provides redundancy.

## Load balancer distribution algorithm

The load balancer is configured with the Round Robin algorithm.

Round Robin sends requests to each server one after another.

Example:

```text
Request 1 -> Server 1
Request 2 -> Server 2
Request 3 -> Server 1
Request 4 -> Server 2
```

This allows traffic to be shared between the two servers.

## Active-Active or Active-Passive setup

This infrastructure is an Active-Active setup.

In an Active-Active setup, all servers are running and serving traffic at the same time.

In an Active-Passive setup, one server is active and handles the traffic, while another server stays on standby. The passive server is only used if the active server fails.

## Database Primary-Replica cluster

A Primary-Replica database cluster means there is one main database server called the Primary node and one or more Replica nodes.

The Primary node receives all write operations, such as:

* INSERT
* UPDATE
* DELETE

The Replica node copies data from the Primary node and can be used for read operations, such as:

* SELECT

## Difference between Primary and Replica nodes

The Primary node is used by the application for write operations.

The Replica node is used mainly for read operations and backup/redundancy.

Example:

```text
Create user -> Primary database
Read user profile -> Replica database
```

The Replica database must stay synchronized with the Primary database.

## Issues with this infrastructure

### Single Point of Failure

There are still SPOFs in this infrastructure.

The load balancer is a SPOF because there is only one HAProxy server.

If the load balancer fails, users cannot access the website.

The Primary database is also a SPOF for write operations.

If the Primary database fails, the application cannot write new data.

### Security issues

This infrastructure has security problems.

There is no firewall, so the servers are more exposed to attacks.

There is also no HTTPS, which means communication between the user and the website is not encrypted.

Sensitive data could be intercepted.

### No monitoring

There is no monitoring system.

This means administrators cannot easily detect:

* server failures
* high traffic
* database problems
* application errors
* disk or memory issues

Without monitoring, it is harder to react quickly when something goes wrong.
